08852nam a22009975i 9780228009115DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280091157 a10.1515/97802280091152doi  a(DE-B1597)655162  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a305.89707100aRoyally Wronged :bThe Royal Society of Canada and Indigenous Peoples /ced. by Constance Backhouse, Adele Perry, Margaret Kovach, Cynthia E. Milton. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b20 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tThe Royal Society of Canada and Colonialism: The Legacy of Duncan Campbell Scott -- tThe Royal Society of Canada and the Marginalization of Indigenous Knowledge -- tThe Royal Society of Canada’s Historic Role -- tRather of Promise than of Performance: Tracing Networks of Knowledge and Power Through the Proceedings and Transactions of the Royal Society of Canada, 1882–1922 -- tDuncan Campbell Scott and the Royal Society of Canada: The Legitimation of Knowledge -- t“Perhaps the white man’s God has willed it so”: Reconsidering the “Indian” Poems of Pauline Johnson and Duncan Campbell Scott -- t“Sooner or later they will be given the privelage [sic] asked for”: Duncan Campbell Scott and the Dispossession of Shoal Lake 40, 1913–14 -- tThe Royal Society of Canada and Academic Writings -- tThree Fellows in Mi’kma’ki: The Power of the Avocational -- t“Not a little disappointment”: Forging Postcolonial Academies from Emulation and Exclusion -- tNostra Culpa? Reflections on “The Indian in Canadian Historical Writing” -- tRethinking Academia and Indigeneity -- tForensic Anthropology and Archaeology as Tools for Reconciliation in Investigations into Unmarked Graves at Indian Residential Schools -- tConfronting “Cognitive Imperialism”: What Reconstituting a Contracts Law School Course is Teaching Me about Law -- tMurder They Wrote: “Unknown Knowns” and Windsor Law’s Statement Regarding R. v. Stanley -- tHistory in the Public Interest: Teaching Decolonization Through the RSC Archive -- tCause and Effect: The Invisible Barriers of the Royal Society of Canada -- tFuture Directions -- tMemorandum to the Royal Society of Canada -- tGolden Eagle Rising: A Conversation on Indigenous Knowledge -- tClosing Circle Words -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Royal Society of Canada’s mandate is to elect to its membership leading scholars in the arts, humanities, social sciences, and sciences, lending its seal of excellence to those who advance artistic and intellectual knowledge in Canada. Duncan Campbell Scott, one of the architects of the Indian residential school system in Canada, served as the society’s president and dominated its activities; many other members – historically overwhelmingly white men – helped shape knowledge systems rooted in colonialism that have proven catastrophic for Indigenous communities.Written primarily by current Royal Society of Canada members, these essays explore the historical contribution of the RSC and of Canadian scholars to the production of ideas and policies that shored up white settler privilege, underpinning the disastrous interaction between Indigenous peoples and white settlers. Historical essays focus on the period from the RSC’s founding in 1882 to the mid-twentieth century; later chapters bring the discussion to the present, documenting the first steps taken to change damaging patterns and challenging the society and Canadian scholars to make substantial strides toward a better future.The highly educated in Canadian society were not just bystanders: they deployed their knowledge and skills to abet colonialism. This volume dives deep into the RSC’s history to learn why academia has more often been an aid to colonialism than a force against it. Royally Wronged poses difficult questions about what is required – for individual academics, fields of study, and the RSC – to move meaningfully toward reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aIndian Canadian scholarly writing.  aIndigenous knowledge.  acolonial settler research.  acritical race studies.  adecolonisation.  aduncan campbell scott.  aerasure Indigenous expertise.  aexclusion outsiders.  aexclusive fellowship.  alegitimation knowledge.  anetworks knowledge.  apauline johnson.  apost colonial academy.  aroyal society canada.  atruth reconciliation.  awhite elite scholarship.1 aAlbanese, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBackhouse, Constance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBackhouse, Constance, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBahdi, Reem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackstock, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreault, Meagan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuschek, Ellis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardoso, Hugo F.V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerson, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Shain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca